  <Notes>
    <Note Caller="1" LanguageCode="en" LastEdited="" LastEditedBy="">
      <References/>
      <Content>As in the case of other so-called semantic derivatives, it seems best in this instance likewise to employ only evident glosses. One could, of course define the process of hearing as ‘perceiving by means of the ears,’ but such a definition would be unnecessarily artificial.</Content>
    </Note>
    <Note Caller="2" LanguageCode="en" LastEdited="" LastEditedBy="">
      <References/>
      <Content>The idiom κνήθομαι τὴν ἀκοήν involves two quite distinct semantic features. One is the desire to be pleased, and the second is the means of such gratification, namely, what is heard. It would be possible to classify this idiom either under Sensory Events and States (Domain 24) or here in the domain of Attitudes and Emotions. Since in {S:05500400300040} the latter seems the more focal feature of meaning, the idiom is included at this point.</Content>
    </Note>
